Part 1: Load the data, log charges, create train and test sets

df <- read.csv('insurance.csv')

df$log_charges <- log(df$charges)

set.seed(1)

index <- sample(1:nrow(df), size = round(0.7*nrow(df)))

train <- df[index, ]
test <- df[-index, ]

Now we can check out the data

summary(train)

We see that we can make sex, smoker, and region into factors.

train$sex <- as.factor(train$sex)
train$smoker <- as.factor(train$smoker)
train$region <- as.factor(train$region)

test$sex <- as.factor(test$sex)
test$smoker <- as.factor(test$smoker)
test$region <- as.factor(test$region)

Part 2: Building a linear regression model

lin_model = lm(log_charges ~ age + sex + smoker+bmi+children+ region, data= train)
summary(lin_model)

From our model, we can see from the p-value that age, sex, smoker, bmi, children, and region all have significant impact on charges. Sex does indeed have a significant impact on the response. We can see from the coefficient that being male has a negative impact on our response, since the coefficient is negative. Now we will make predictions in order to calculate the rmse.

linear_predictions <- predict(lin_model, newdata = test)
linear_rmse <- sqrt(mean((test$log_charges - linear_predictions)^2))
print(linear_rmse)
## [1] 0.4892747

Part 3: Building a regression tree model

tree_model <- tree(log_charges ~ age + sex + smoker+bmi+children+ region, data= train)
tm_cv <- cv.tree(tree_model)
plot(tm_cv$size, tm_cv$dev, type='b')

Here, we can tell that three is the optimal number of clusters, as it is the elbow point in the graph. This is generally represents a good point with regards to the variance-bias tradeoff. That is to say there is not that much of a drop in variances in branches beyond 3, which means that additional bias towards this dataset, as well as significant computational complexity will be introduced inefficiently beyond this point. We can now proceed with pruning the tree.

insurance_prune <- prune.tree(tree_model, best=3)
plot(insurance_prune)
text(insurance_prune, pretty=0)

This is a plot of our tree with the amount of branches we determined was optimal in the last step. Now let’s calculate the RMSE.

yhat <- predict(insurance_prune, newdata = test)
test_results <- test[, 'log_charges']
tree_rmse <- mean((yhat - test_results)^2)
tree_rmse
## [1] 0.2979018

The above number is the calculation of the RMSE for our tree model.

Part 4: Building a random forest model.

rf_insurance <- randomForest(log_charges ~ age + sex + smoker+bmi+children+ region, data= train, importance= TRUE)

Next we can compute the RMSE for the random forest model, and compare it to the previous models.

rf_yhat <- predict(rf_insurance, newdata=test)
rf_test_results <- test[, 'log_charges']
rf_rmse <- mean((rf_yhat -rf_test_results)^2)
rf_rmse
## [1] 0.1867766

From this value, we can see that the RMSE for the random forest is significantly better than both the singular tree, and the linear model from part 2. We can also plot the importance of the different predictors.

importance(rf_insurance)
##             %IncMSE IncNodePurity
## age      103.240158    248.643942
## sex        1.460505      6.917457
## smoker   145.691046    329.997250
## bmi       21.955607     58.679135
## children  31.430673     33.950714
## region     9.058671     17.182018
varImpPlot(rf_insurance)

From the results of the plot, and the %IncMSE and IncNodePurity, we can tell that smoker and age are by far the most significant features in our model. The third is a bit harder to determine, since bmi and children are very close in importance, however, if I had to choose one, as node purity is probably more important than the mse when predicting charges, since high cost outliers could feasibly have significant impact on the mean.

Part 5: k-means cluster analysis

First, we need to remove the data that is non-numerical, as mentioned in the instructions,

train_new <- train %>% select(-sex, -region, -charges, -smoker)
test_new <- test %>% select(-sex, -region, -charges, -smoker)

Now we can figure out the correct number of clusters.

fviz_nbclust(train_new, kmeans, method='gap_stat')

We can see that the best number of clusters according to the gap statistic method is 2, as it is almost equal to 3, but two requires less computing power, so we should use less when we can. We can also try with the silhouette method to see if it comes to the same conclusion. Note: A higher gap statistic is better, as it measures the average gap between clusters, a higher number means more distinction between clusters.

fviz_nbclust(train_new, kmeans, method='silhouette')

The silhouette method also found that two is the most efficient number of clusters to use with our data. Now we can visualize the clusters

km_result1<- kmeans(train_new, 2, nstart=25)
fviz_cluster(km_result1, data=train_new)

Part 6: Putting it all together.

In terms of which model is best for our data, we can compare RMSEs. We can do that in tabular format.

Model.Type <- c("Multiple Linear Regression", "Regression Tree", "Random Forest")
Test.MSE <- c(round(linear_rmse,4), round(tree_rmse,4), round(rf_rmse, 4))
rm_compare <- data.frame(Model.Type, Test.MSE)
print(rm_compare)
##                   Model.Type Test.MSE
## 1 Multiple Linear Regression   0.4893
## 2            Regression Tree   0.2979
## 3              Random Forest   0.1868

Using the above dataframe, we can compare the RMSE from each of the models we have used. By doing this, we can clearly see that the Random Forest model has the lowest RMSE, thus making it the best one to use for determining charges.

In answer to the question regarding which model is easiest to visually demonstrate a feature, I recommend the a regression tree, as the logic of a decision tree is very easy to follow. I would recommend that model over most others if we are mostly focused on ease of understanding.

We can reverse the logarithmic transformation of the charges in order to demonstrate the output of the tree model most simply:

prune.copy <- insurance_prune
prune.copy$frame$yval <- exp(prune.copy$frame$yval)
plot(prune.copy)
text(prune.copy, pretty=0)
